 our rhetoric and composition classes, our creative writing classes, and our community groups? Contributors to Getting Personal offer their thoughts about some of the positives and negatives of teaching and using personal writing within digital contexts. They also reveal intriguing teaching activities that they have designed to engage their students and other writers. In addition, they share some of the innovative responses they have received to these assignments. Getting Personal is about finding ways to teach and use personal writing in the digital age that can truly empower writing teachers, writing students, as well as other community members.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnglish languagexRhetoricxComputer-assisted instruction. 0aEnglish languagexRhetoricxStudy and teachingxTechnological innovations. 0aEssayxAuthorship. 0aOnline authorship. 0aOnline data processingxAuthorshipxStudy and teaching. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Literacy Studies. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / Nonfiction (incl. Memoirs).2bisacsh1 aArrington, Paige, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Lynn Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray-Rosendale, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray-Rosendale, Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarker, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartone, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartorana, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCorkle, Ben, econtributor.